1.name: Erythrai
1.description: Erythrai was one of the twelve Ionian cities of Asia Minor. It is located on a small peninsula that extends into the Bay of Erythrae.

2.name: Ilium/Troia
2.description: An ancient city of northwest Anatolia with occupation ranging from the Bronze Age to the Roman period. Troy features as the central setting of Homer's Iliad.

4.name: Klazomenai (earlier)
4.description: The initial, mainland site of the city, located to the southwest of modern Urla Iskelesi in Turkey. Pausanias reports that the city relocated to an island in the Bay of Smyrna, for which see "Klazomenai (later)."

5.name: Teos
5.description: An ancient Ionian settlement of Asia Minor, located at modern Siğacik in Turkey.

6.name: Pergamum
6.description: An important ancient settlement, located at modern Bergama in Turkey. It was first described in Xenophon's Anabasis and was later used as a treasury under Lysimachus. Pergamum became the administrative capital and principal city of the Attalid kingdom and dynasty (282-133 BCE) and was briefly the first capital of the Roman province of Asia. It later was a seat of a Christian bishopric and is listed in Revelation as one of the seven churches of Asia. It was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2014 under "Pergamon and its Multi-Layered Cultural Landscape".

7.name: Aegae
7.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E4 Aegae

8.name: Mytilene
8.description: An ancient settlement. The early fortified core of the city was located on an islet off the east coast of Lesbos, now joined to the mainland. That site is dominated by the remains of a Byzantine fortress with Ottoman and Genoese repairs and additions. This original city later expanded onto the main island.

9.name: Neapolis (Kavalla)
9.description: An ancient port city on the coast of Thrace, Neapolis (modern Kavalla in the Decentralized Administration of Macedonia and Thrace in Greece) was probably founded from Thasos in the seventh century CE. It served as the port for Philippi in Hellenistic and Roman times, and was refortified by Justinian in the sixth century CE.

10.name: Mende
10.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 A5 Mende

11.name: Thasos (settlement)
11.description: Greeks from Paros founded a colony on Thasos in the middle of the seventh century B.C.

12.name: Torone
12.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B5 Torone

13.name: Akanthos
13.description: An ancient settlement in the northeast of the Chalkidiki. The large site is immediately southeast of the modern town of Ierissos.

14.name: Polyrrenia
14.description: Polyrrenia was an important ancient city of western Crete.

15.name: Bargylia
15.description: An ancient city of Caria, now known in Turkish as Varvıl. The site is located near the modern Turkish village of Boğaziçi in Muğla province.

16.name: Cnidus
16.description: Cnidus, a Greek city of ancient Caria that was part of the Dorian Hexapolis, was located at modern Burgaz in south-western Asia Minor on the modern Datça peninsula (Knidia) in Turkey. In the late fourth century, the political center of the peninsula moved from the site at Burgaz to the site at Tekir.

17.name: Iasos
17.description: Iasos was an ancient Greek city in Caria.

18.name: Heraclea ad Latmum/Pleistarcheia
18.description: A town of Caria located 25 km east of Miletos on the Ionian coast, Heraclea was located on the lower slopes of Mt. Latmos. Once a part of the Delian League, the city fell to Mausolos in the fourth century B.C. and his philhellene policy accounts for its change of name.

19.name: Priene/‘Lince’?
19.description: Priene/‘Lince’? was an ancient Greek city of Ionia on an escarpment of Mycale Mons.

20.name: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia
20.description: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia was an ancient city founded by Argives and Trallians that then fell under the sway of the Persian Empire and, later, Hellenistic kings.

21.name: Mylasa
21.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F3 Mylasa

22.name: Nysa/Athymbra
22.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 G2 Nysa/Athymbra

23.name: Alabanda/Antiocheia Chrysaoron
23.description: Alabanda/Antiocheia Chrysaoron was an ancient city of Caria.

24.name: Alinda/Alexandria ad Latmum
24.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F2 Alinda/Alexandria ad Latmum

25.name: Magnesia ad Maeandrum/Leukophrys
25.description: Magnesia ad Maeandrum was an ancient city on the Maeander River in Ionia, site of an important sanctuary of Artemis Leukophryene ("of the white eyebrow").

26.name: Parium/Col. Gemella Iulia *Hadriana
26.description: Founded as a Greek city in the Propontis region of Anatolia, perhaps ca. 709 BCE, Persians would come to control Parium in 546 BCE. The city allied itself with Athens during the Peloponnesian War, but was subsequently ruled again by the Persians again. Its long occupation included a Macedonian phase, followed by control exercise by the Seleucids, the Kingdom of Pergamon, the Romans, and the Byzantines.

27.name: Prusias ad Mare/Kios
27.description: Prusias ad Mare/Kios was an ancient Greek city on the Propontis. The city joined the Aetolian League and was destroyed by Philip V of Macedon. Prusias I of Bithynia rebuilt the site, naming it for himself.

28.name: Zeleia
28.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Zeleia

29.name: Cyzicus
29.description: An ancient city of Mysia in Anatolia, perhaps founded by the Corinthians in 756 BC and then again by the Milesians ca. 675 BC. Its advantageous position in the Propontis made it a major commercial centre. In the 5th century BC it was part of the Delian League and in the Hellenistic Age it was close to the Attalid kings. In the Imperial period, it became an assize centre (conventus) of the province of Asia.

30.name: Helikore/Nicaea
30.description: Helikore/Nicaea (modern İznik, Turkey) was a Greek city of northwestern Anatolia. It was the site of the First and Second Councils of Nicaea and was the interim capital city of the Byzantine Empire between 1204 and 1261.

31.name: Peiraieus/Piraeus
31.description: The ancient, fortified port settlement of ancient Athens. It was also the coastal deme of the tribe Hippothoontis.

32.name: Thorikos
32.description: Thorikos was a coastal deme of the tribe Akamantis, in southeastern Attica. A significant Mycenaean prescence existed at the site during the Bronze Age.

33.name: Tanagra
33.description: Tanagra was an ancient settlement of Boeotia.

34.name: Lyktos
34.description: An ancient settlement on Crete, located just east of modern Xydas/Xidas, with which it is sometimes conflated. The city is mentioned in Homer and seems to have flourished in Hellenistic and Roman times, at least.

35.name: Phalasarna
35.description: An ancient harbor town located on the northwest coast of Crete.

36.name: Knosos/Col. Iulia Nobilis Cnosos
36.description: A major ancient settlement of Crete located some 5 km southeast of Heraklion, Knossos was occupied from the Neolithic period to the time of the Roman empire.

37.name: Itanos
37.description: An ancient coastal settlement of east Crete. The site is located north of the palm forest at Vai and has provided evidence for occupation from the archaic period through late antiquity.

38.name: Corcyra (settlement)
38.description: The eponymous settlement of the island of Corcyra (modern Korfu).

39.name: Ambracia
39.description: Ambracia (modern Arta) was an ancient city of central Greece, founded as a colony of Corinth in the seventh century BC. It was located near the Ambracian Gulf along the course of the river Arachthos.

40.name: Phoinike
40.description: Phoinike was an ancient Greek city of Epirus and the location of the Treaty of Phoenice which ended the First Macedonian War.

41.name: Oiniadai
41.description: A city at the former mouth of the Achelous river.

42.name: Stratos
42.description: Stratos was the chief town of Acarnania. Modern Sourovigli in Greece.

43.name: Thyrreion
43.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Thyrreion

44.name: Aidepsos (spa)
44.description: A famous Euboean spa city in the Hellenistic and Roman periods, located at modern Loutra Aidepsou. The polis' original location may have been 3-4 km north in the area of a modern town that carries the modern name Aidepsos (previously Lipso).

45.name: Calydon
45.description: An ancient Greek city of Aetolia that derives its name from its founder Calydon, son of Aetolus.

46.name: Atrax
46.description: An ancient Greek polis in Pelasgiotis in Thessaly. The site is located in modern Greece, immediately south of the Peneios river and 2.5 km west of a small village named Κάστρο (Kastro), which is within the municipality of Larissa.

47.name: Akraiphiai
47.description: An ancient town of Boeotia located on the eastern edge of the former Lake Copais.

48.name: Nea Pleuron
48.description: Second site of the ancient Greek city of Pleuron, built after the destruction of the original location in the 3rd century BCE. This second site boasts significant excavated remains and is located on the southern slope of Mount Aracynthus near modern Kato Retsina.

49.name: Lilaia
49.description: Ancient Lilaia (modern Kato Agoriani/Pyrgos in Greece) was an ancient Phocean city.

50.name: Orchomenos/Orchomenus
50.description: The so-called "Boeotian Orchomenos", located in the vicinity of the Byzantine church of Panaghia Skripou. The longer, modern title is used to distinguish this settlement from another Greek site with the same ancient name located in Arcadia in the Peloponnese.

51.name: Larissa
51.description: The ancient capital of the Thessalian Pelasgiotis, modern Larisa in Greece.

52.name: Larisa Kremaste/Pelasgia
52.description: An ancient settlement of Achaea Phthiotis, located in the area of the modern town of Pelasgia in Greece.

53.name: Haliartos
53.description: Haliartos was an ancient city of Boeotia, founded as a contemporary of Orchomenos. The city was destroyed by C. Lucretius during the Third Macedonian War. There is a modern Greek town adjacent to the site, which now carries the ancient name.

54.name: Hyettos
54.description: An ancient settlement of Boeotia. The site is located about 2 km east of modern Loutsi in Greece.

55.name: Krannon/Ephyra
55.description: An ancient Thessalian settlement, with evidence of occupation in the area stretching back to the Neolithic.

56.name: Kierion
56.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C2 Kierion

57.name: Demetrias (Magnesian)
57.description: This ancient city, located near modern Volos in Thessaly, was founded by Demetrios Poliorketes in the third century BCE and abandoned in the 6th century CE. Continuous human activity in the area can be traced back at least as early as the Neolithic.

58.name: Chaeronea
58.description: An ancient settlement of Boeotia, Chaeronea was a subject of Orchomenus and a member of the Boeotian League. From the late fifth century BC, Chaeronea belonged to one of the 11 Boeotian districts.

59.name: Elateia
59.description: Elateia was an ancient Greek city of Phocis, and numbered as the most important place in that region after Delphi. The remains of the ancient site are located to the northeast of the modern town.

60.name: Pyrasos
60.description: Ancient Pyrasos in Thessaly overlooked the Bay of Volo. Its site is occupied by the modern Néa Anchiálos (Magnesia, Thessaly, Greece).

61.name: Pharsalus
61.description: Pharsalus was one of the most important cities of ancient Thessaly.

62.name: Plataea
62.description: Plataea is an ancient city of Boeotia, located south of Thebes. In 479 BC Plataea was the site of the Battle of Plataea, in which an allied Greek army defeated the Persians. Plataea was destroyed in the Peloponnesian War by Thebes and Sparta in 427 BC and rebuilt in 386 BC.

63.name: Styra
63.description: Styra was an ancient port city located in the southwestern part of Euboea that possessed also an inland acropolis (on the modern peak of Hagios Nikolaos), extensive quarries, and a series of large stone structures known today as drakospita (dragon's houses).

64.name: Thebai Phthiotides
64.description: A city located in the northern part of the ancient Krokian plain, near modern Akitsi/Mikrothivai.

65.name: Thermon
65.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B3 Thermon

66.name: Thisbe
66.description: Thisbe was an ancient town of Boeotia located on the southern flank of Mt. Helicon.

67.name: Thespiai
67.description: Thespiai was an ancient city of Boeotia, located at the foot of Mt. Helicon.

68.name: Phigaleia
68.description: Phigaleia was an ancient city in the southwestern part of Arcadia in Greece.

69.name: Pheneos
69.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C2 Pheneos

70.name: Patra(e)
70.description: Patra(e) (modern Patras) is an important ancient center with settlement beginning in the Late Helladic period. Patras played a leading role in the foundation of the second "Achaean League" and was the site of a Roman colony after 146 BC.

71.name: Orchomenos (Arcadia)
71.description: The so-called "Arcadian Orchomenos", located near a modern village in the Peloponnese that, until the 1960s, was known as Kalpaki.

72.name: Sparta
72.description: Sparta was a prominent city-state (polis) of ancient Greece.

73.name: Stymphalos
73.description: Stymphalos was a small but wealthy city of ancient Arcadia.

74.name: Phleious
74.description: An ancient city located in the valley of the river Asopos.

75.name: Sicyon/Demetrias
75.description: Sicyon/Demetrias was an important ancient city of the Corinthiad, located some 26 km to the west of Corinth. The city had a long history, beginning in the Archaic period when Orthagorid tyrants ruled it. It flourished in later Archaic and Classical times, was a member of the Peloponnesian League, and became a center of Theban power after 371 B.C. The city was long noted for its association with fine arts and during the fourth century B.C. produced the famous sculptor Lysippos. Under Aratos, Sicyon joined the Achaean League in 251 B.C. By the time Pausanias visited the site, declining political fortunes and disastrous earthquakes had reduced it to a ruinous state.

76.name: Aigeira
76.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C1 Aigeira

77.name: Corinthus/Korinthos
77.description: The ancient Greek and Roman city of Corinth, located in the Peloponnese, Greece. Also known today as Archaia Korinthos and not to be confused with the nearby modern town.

78.name: Asine
78.description: Asine was an ancient Greek city of Argolis.

79.name: Hysiai
79.description: Hysiai was a frontier citadel of Argos located to the south of the modern village of Achladokampos. The Lacedaemonians destroyed the site in 417 B.C. Pausanias visited the ruined settlement, while Curtius described the remains of the fortifications.

80.name: Kenchreai
80.description: The ancient Saronic Gulf port of Corinth (near modern Kechries in Greece).

81.name: Methana/Arsinoe
81.description: Methana/Arsinoe refers to a peninsula and settlement located on the north coast of the Argolid. In geological terms, the peninsula is formed by relatively recent volcanic activity, with the last-known eruptive activity in the third century BCE. Human activity on the peninsula spans many periods. The chief polity was located in the southwest of the peninsula where the modern village of Megalochori is found today.

84.name: Methone/Mothone (Messenian)
84.description: An ancient settlement sited on the west coast of the Messenian peninsula of the Peloponnese. The collocated modern settlement is called Methoni and is located in the administratively part of the Pylos-Nestoras municipality, Messenia regional unit, of the modern Greek state.

85.name: Mantineia/Antigoneia
85.description: Mantineia/Antigoneia was an ancient settlement in Greece most noted for being the site of two major battles. The First Battle of Mantineia was the largest land battle of the Peloponnesian War (418 B.C.) and the Second Battle of Mantineia brought an end to Theban hegemony (362 B.C.).

86.name: Lykosoura
86.description: A city of Arcadia and home of the cult of Despoina

87.name: Epidauros Limera
87.description: An ancient settlement on the east coast of Lakonia. The site, sometimes referred to today as Palaia Monemvasia, has produced evidence for habitation dating from at least the Late Helladic period to perhaps as late as the 6th century CE.

88.name: Gyth(e)ion
88.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D4 Gyth(e)ion

89.name: Epidauros
89.description: Epidauros is located on a small peninsula on the eastern coast of Peloponnesus.

90.name: Halieis
90.description: An ancient Greek harbor city in the Argolid (across from the modern village of Porto Cheli) that was abandoned toward the end of the fourth century BCE. Excavated remains include fortification walls (as early as the eighth century BCE), a city with an orthogonal street plan, an industrial quarter, and domestic architecture with evidence for agricultural processing. Parts of the city are now under water due to a rise in sea levels.

91.name: Elis (city)
91.description: Elis was an ancient Greek city of the northwest Peloponnese that served as the capital of the district of the same name.

92.name: Troizen
92.description: An ancient settlement, located in the Peloponnese.

93.name: Tainaron (settlement)
93.description: An ancient settlement, located near the tip of a southern peninsula of the Peloponnese (modern Cape Matapon in Greece). The site featured a sanctuary of Poseidon and served as both a port and a mercenary staging and recruitment area at least as early as the Classical period.

94.name: Tegea
94.description: Tegea was an ancient city of Arcadia. It is especially noted for its sanctuary dedicated to Athena Alea.

95.name: Euonymon
95.description: A classical deme of Attica, located at modern Trachones / Ano Kalamaki. The area has been continuously exploited or inhabited by humans since at least the Neolithic period.

96.name: Eleusis
96.description: Eleusis, located some 22 km west of Athens, was the site of the cult of Demeter and the sanctuary in which the Eleusinian Mysteries were celebrated from the Bronze Age to the Roman Imperial period. It was a coastal deme of the tribe Hippothoontis and site of a military garrison in the Classical and Hellenistic periods.

97.name: Amarynthos
97.description: An ancient coastal settlement on the island of Euboea, located at modern Palaiokhoria/Kato Vathia (just east of the modern Amarynthos).

98.name: Aigina (settlement)
98.description: The primary ancient settlement on the Aegean island of the same name.

99.name: Aphidna
99.description: A large Attic deme, located on the Gulf of Kotroni.

100.name: Oeniandos/Epiphaneia
100.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C3 Oeniandos/Epiphaneia

101.name: Samosata
101.description: An ancient city on the Euphrates River's West bank, established perhaps as early as the Hittite period. Its ruins, known in modern times as Samsat (Turkey), were submerged following the construction of the Atatürk Dam in the early 1990s. The modern village of Samsat was relocated and is not coincident with the ancient site.

102.name: Hydatos Potamoi/Seleukeia Pieria
102.description: The capital city of Seleucus I Nicator, established ca. 300 BC.

103.name: Pella/Apamea
103.description: Pella/Apamea in Syria was an ancient city established by the Seleucids ca. 300 B.C.

104.name: Tripolis
104.description: The Phoenicians established a commercial outpost at Tripolis (Tripoli) in the ninth century BC. An independent city during the Hellenistic period, Tripolis came under Roman control in 64 BC.

105.name: Pteria
105.description: A large, fortified settlement of Anatolia mentioned by Herodotus.

106.name: Marisa
106.description: A Judean, Edomite, and later Hellenistic settlement. Destroyed ca. 40 BCE by the Parthians.

107.name: Phaselis
107.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 E4 Phaselis

108.name: Patara/Arsinoe
108.description: Patara/Arsinoe was an ancient maritime center of southwest Lycia.

109.name: Phellos
109.description: A Lycian settlement located near modern Çukurbağ.

110.name: Perge
110.description: An ancient Greek city of Asia Minor and capital of Pamphylia.

111.name: Sagalassos
111.description: Sagalassos is an ancient city in Pisidia that was later part of the Roman province of Galatia. The city flourished until natural disasters and disease led to its decline in the sixth century AD.

112.name: Pinara
112.description: Pinara was a city of Lycia located at the foot of Mount Cragus (now Mount Babadağ).

113.name: Sillyon
113.description: Sillyon was an ancient Graeco-Pamphylian fortress and city near Attaleia in Pamphylia, on the southern coast Asia Minor.

114.name: Side
114.description: An ancient settlement on the southern coast of Asia Minor (modern Selimiye in Turkey).

116.name: Termessos
116.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 D4 Termessos

117.name: Telmessos
117.description: Telmessos (modern Fethiye) was an ancient city of Lycia.

118.name: Laodicea ad Lycum/Diospolis/Roas
118.description: "Laodicea on the Lycus": an ancient settlement located near the modern village of Eskihisar (Eski Hissar) in Denizli Province, Turkey.

119.name: Colossae
119.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 B2 Colossae

120.name: Gagai/Palaion Teichos
120.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 D5 Gagai/Palaion Teichos

121.name: Caunus
121.description: An ancient city of Caria in southwest Asia Minor.

122.name: Apamea/Kelainai/Kibotos
122.description: Apamea/Kelainai/Kibotos (modern Dinar) was an ancient settlement of Phrygia located at a road junction linking Ionia to the east. In 333 BC Alexander the Great installed his general Antigonos as satrap of Phrygia.

123.name: Aspendos/Primoupolis
123.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 F4 Aspendos/Primoupolis

124.name: Anemurium
124.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 B4 Anemurium

125.name: Celenderis
125.description: An ancient city on the southern coast of Asia Minor at modern Aydıncık in Turkey's Mersin province. It was a major pottery producer and exporter during the Achaemenid period.

126.name: Isaura (Nova)/Leontopolis
126.description: An ancient settlement, modern Zengibar Kalesi in Turkey.

127.name: Laranda
127.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 C2 Laranda

128.name: Iconium/Claudiconium
128.description: Iconium/Claudiconium (modern Konya) was an important city in Lycaonia that later became part of the Roman province of Galatia.

129.name: Soloi/Pompeiopolis
129.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 F3 Soloi/Pompeiopolis

130.name: Melitene
130.description: Melitene was an ancient city on the Tohma River. It was the station of Legio XII Fulminata from AD 70 onwards.

131.name: Sebasteia/Megalopolis?/Talaura?
131.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 E1 Sebasteia/Megalopolis?/Talaura?

132.name: Comana/Hierapolis/Chryse
132.description: Comana/Hierapolis/Chryse was an ancient city in Cappadocia.

133.name: Ake/Ptolemais
133.description: The Phoenician city of Akko was re-founded by Ptolemy II Philadelphos from ca. 285-246 B.C.

134.name: Dor(a)
134.description: A coastal settlement of Phoenicia, now Tel Dor to the south of Haifa.

135.name: Neapolis
135.description: After the sacking of Jerusalem, Vespasian settled Roman veterans on a new town site located between Mt. Gerizim and Mt. Ebal. The new Roman colony was built on the site of Mabartha.

137.name: Bactra/Zariaspa
137.description: An ancient city of what is now northern Afghanistan. Bactra/Zariaspa (modern Balkh) was a center of Zoroastrianism.

138.name: Rhaga(i)/Europos/Arsakia/Ray
138.description: Rhaga(i), now the city of Rey in Iran, was an important settlement of the Medes that declined after the Mongol invasions.

139.name: Ur(i)
139.description: A major Sumerian city-state founded during the Ubaid period, ca. 3800 B.C. In archaeological terms, Ur is particularly well known for the lavish tombs of its Royal Cemetery, its massive Ziggurat. The site served as the capital of the Ur III dynasty.

140.name: Hecatompylos?/Komish/[(Shahr-i) Qumis]
140.description: Hecatompylos? was an ancient city in Iran that served as the capital of the Parthian Arsacid dynasty by 200 B.C. Alexander passed through in 330 B.C. and the city eventually became part of the Seleucid Empire and later a capital of the Parthian Empire.

141.name: Pasargadae/Batrakatash
141.description: Pasargadae/Batrakatash was an ancient Persian city and the capital of Cyrus the Great (559–530 BC). It remained the capital until Cambyses II moved it to Susa. The site is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

142.name: Qasr-i Abu Nasr/Seraz/Tirazzish?/Shiraz(zish)?
142.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 94 C4 Qasr-i Abu Nasr/Seraz/Tirazzish?/Shiraz(zish)?

143.name: Tarmita/Termez
143.description: Termez, located in modern Uzbekistan, was part of the Graeco-Bactrian kingdom and later the Kushan empire. It eventually became an important center of Buddhism.

144.name: Col. Vienna
144.description: A settlement of the Allobroges in Gallia Narbonensis that became a Roman colony in 47 BC.

145.name: Hermonassa
145.description: An Ionian colony on the Gulf of Taman.

146.name: Pantikapaion/Bosp(h)orus
146.description: The main city and port of the Kimmerian Bosporus, founded by Miletus in the late seventh or early sixth centuries B.C. Modern Kerch.

147.name: Trapezus
147.description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor on the south coast of the Black Sea. Modern Trabzon in Turkey.

148.name: Phasis (settlement)
148.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 G2 Phasis

149.name: Kotais
149.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 88 A2 Kotais

150.name: Gorneae
150.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 88 C4 Gorneae

151.name: Meroe
151.description: Meroë is an ancient city located on the east bank of the Nile river near Shendi, Sudan. The city was a center of the kingdom of Kush.

152.name: Kawa
152.description: Known today as Kawa, ruins of this ancient Egyptian and Kushite settlement are located on the east bank of the Nile river, seven kilometers south of the modern Nile bridge at Dongola in Sudan.

153.name: Dedan/al-'Ula
153.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 83 C5 Dedan/al-'Ula

154.name: Heraclea
154.description: An ancient settlement on the Black Sea coast of Asia Minor at modern Karadeniz Ereğli in Turkey. It is often referred to as Heraclea Pontica (or Heraclea in Pontus) to distinguish it from other cities with the same name.

155.name: Gorgippia/Sindikos Limen
155.description: Gorgippia/Sindikos Limen was a sixth century B.C. colony founded by Pontic Greeks on the site of Sinda.

156.name: Resaina/Theodosiopolis
156.description: A Roman garrison town located near the Chaboras that was later renamed Theodosiopolis.

157.name: Vicetia
157.description: Vicetia (modern Vicenza) as a settlement of the Veneti in northern Italy.

158.name: Felsina/Bononia
158.description: A city of the Po Plain with important cultural phases related to Etruscan, Celtic, and Roman culture. Important evidence for the Iron Age Villanovan culture has been found in Bononia and its vicinity. The Romans established a Latin colony of 3000 settlers at Bononia in 189 BC. After changing hands several times following the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Bologna became an important Medieval center.

159.name: Neapolis
159.description: Neapolis (modern Nabeul, Tunisia) is a coastal town on the Cap Bon peninsula that was founded by Greeks from Cyrene in the fifth century B.C.

160.name: Utica
160.description: A Punic center located west of Carthage.

161.name: Mediolan(i)um
161.description: A Celtic settlement and crossroads, later a Western Roman capital. Now modern Milan, Italy.

162.name: Gigthis
162.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 35 C1 Gigthis

163.name: Oea
163.description: Phoenicians established Oea in the seventh century B.C. and it later became a Roman–Berber colony. Modern-day Tripoli, Libya.

164.name: Neapolis/Lepcis Magna
164.description: Originally a Phoenician colony founded ca. 1100 B.C., Lepcis Magna became a prominent Roman city and birthplace of the emperor Septimius Severus.

165.name: Ptolemais/Barkes Limen
165.description: An ancient capital of Cyrenaica, Ptolemais was probably named after Ptolemy III Euergetes. The city was founded in either the seventh or sixth century BC.

166.name: Darnis
166.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Darnis

167.name: Euesperides
167.description: Euesperides was the westernmost Greek colony of Cyrenaica. The remains of the site are found on the outskirts of modern Benghazi near the north Libyan coast. Under Ptolemy III Euergetes, the new city of Berenice was built a short distance southwest of Euesperides and the original site was subsequently abandoned.

168.name: Augila
168.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 C4 Augila

169.name: Cyrene
169.description: An ancient Greek city founded in eastern Libya ca. 630 B.C., Cyrene later became part of the Roman empire (ca. 74 B.C.). The site was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1982.

170.name: Barke
170.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 B1 Barke

171.name: Arsinoe/Taucheira
171.description: Arsinoe/Taucheira (modern Tocra) may have originally been a Greek foundation that was part of Pentapolis of Cyrenaica. It eventually became a Roman colony and, by the time of Justinian, was fortified.

172.name: Croto(n)
172.description: An Achaean colony in Magna Graecia established in 710 BC by the oikist Myscellus from the city of Rhypes in the Peloponnese.

173.name: Lokroi Epizephyrioi
173.description: Locri is a town and comune in the province of Reggio Calabria, Calabria, in southern Italy. Epizephyrian Locris was founded ca. 680 BC near modern Capo Zefirio, by the Locrians, apparently under the Opuntii (East Locrians) from the city of Opus, but also including Ozolae (West Locrians) and Lacedaemonians.

174.name: Heraclea
174.description: Heraclea was an ancient city of Magna Graecia.

175.name: Velia/Elea
175.description: The ancient city of Elea / Velia was said to have been founded by Phocaean Greeks in the sixth century B.C. and then became an ally of Rome in the third century B.C.

176.name: Tauromenium
176.description: Tauromenium was an ancient city in Sicily founded in 358 B.C.

177.name: Thermae Himeraeae
177.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Thermae Himeraeae

178.name: Monte Adranone (Adranon?)
178.description: An indigenous center of the eighth to fourth centuries B.C. that became Hellenized, Monte Adranone in Sicily is probably to be identified with the ancient name Adranon.

179.name: Akragas/Agrigentum
179.description: Akragas/Agrigentum was an ancient city of Sicily and is now known as Agrigento. The Archaeological Area of Agrigento was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

180.name: Camarina
180.description: Camarina was founded by Syracuse in 599 B.C., but subsequently destroyed in 552 B.C. The city was re-founded by Gela in 461 B.C. Carthage razed the site in 405 B.C., but Timoleon restored it in 339 B.C. From the late third century B.C. the town fell under Roman administration.

181.name: Morgantina
181.description: An indigenous Sicilian site founded by the Morgeti, according to Strabo, Morgantina was eventually defeated by Syracuse and thus, in turn, passed into Roman hegemony in the third century B.C.

182.name: Megara Hyblaia
182.description: Megara Hyblaia was an ancient Greek colony in eastern Sicily founded in the eighth century B.C.

183.name: Soluntum
183.description: An ancient settlement on the north-west coast of Sicily, some 16 km east of modern Palermo.

184.name: Segesta/Egesta
184.description: A center of the Elymian people in northwestern Sicily.

185.name: Heraclea Minoa
185.description: An ancient Greek city on the south coast of Sicily located at the mouth of the Halykos River. Founded by Selinus in the sixth century BC, the site was abandoned in the first century AD.

186.name: Lipara (settlement)
186.description: A Greek colony and long-time settlement on the island of the same name, located to the north of Sicily in the Tyrrhenian Sea. Modern Lipari.

187.name: Lilybaeum
187.description: Lilybaeum (modern Marsala) is located at the extreme westernmost point of Sicily. Lilybaeum was a Punic settlement that was conquered by the Romans in 241 B.C.

188.name: Himera
188.description: A colony on the north shore of Sicily founded in 649/8 BC by the Myletidai.

189.name: Gela
189.description: A Greek colony of Sicily founded by Rhodians and Cretans ca. 688 B.C. The oikists were the Rhodian Antiphemos and the Cretan Entimos.

190.name: Leontini
190.description: A Greek colonial city founded by Naxians in 729 B.C., Leontini was reduced by Hippocrates of Gela in 498 B.C. Following the Sicilian Expedition, the city became subject to Syracuse. In Roman times it may have been of little importance and was destroyed by the Saracens in A.D. 848.

191.name: Fufluna/Populonium
191.description: Populonia likely derives its name from the Etruscan god 'Fufluns' and was an important maritime and commercial center of Etruria located in the Colline Metallifere.

192.name: Vatl/Vetulonia
192.description: The Etruscan Vatluna resisted Rome's influence in the seventh century BCE, although the city may have been the source of Rome's adoption of the curule chair and the fasces.

193.name: Pisae
193.description: A city situated on the Tyrrhenian seaboard and likely of Etruscan origin. Its early nature was that of a mercantile center. The city became a Roman colony in 89 B.C.

194.name: Velathri/Volaterrae
194.description: A major Etruscan city of North Etruria.

195.name: Ber(r)oia
195.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 B3 Ber(r)oia

197.name: Aigeai
197.description: An ancient settlement most noted for the discovery, in 1977, of Macedonian royal tombs at the site.

198.name: Dion
198.description: Dion was a settlement of Pieria located on the border between Macedonia and Thessaly. It was held, traditionally, as the place of Orpheus' death and burial. In the Roman Imperial period, it became a Roman colonia. The adjacent modern village, now known as Dion, is sometimes also referenced by its earlier modern name Malathria.

199.name: Methone (Pieria)
199.description: An ancient settlement in Macedonian Pieria on a hilltop named Koryphi, near modern Nea Agathoupolis in the Pydna-Kalindros municipality in Pieria, Greece. The site was occupied from the Late Neolithic period (ca. 4000 BCE) through 354 BCE, when it was destroyed by the armies of Philip II. It was succeeded by a new settlement approximately 1km to the northwest; known as Macedonian Methone, this later settlement was occupied in the Hellenistic and Roman periods.

200.name: Herakleia Sintike
200.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D2 Herakleia Sintike

201.name: Olynthos
201.description: Olynthos was an ancient city of the Chalcidice, founded in the seventh century B.C. and destroyed in 348 B.C. by the forces of Philip II of Macedon.

202.name: Thessalonica
202.description: A city of northern Greece founded by Cassander of Macedon ca. 315 BC; important center of the Roman and Late Antique worlds.

203.name: Anxanum
203.description: City of the Frentani, situated on a hill about 5 miles from the Adriatic Sea, and 8 miles from the mouth of the river Sagrus or Sangro in Italy.

204.name: Cluviae
204.description: A city of the Carricini Samnites.

205.name: Asisium
205.description: A Roman settlement built atop an earlier Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Apennines, Asisium received municipal status and was assigned to the Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.

206.name: *Aurinia/Saturnia
206.description: An Etruscan town that Dionysius of Halicarnassus claimed had been founded by the Pelasgians, Saturnia received a Roman colony in 183 BC.

207.name: Ancon(a)
207.description: A port city founded by colonists from Syracuse in 387 BC.

208.name: Arna
208.description: Arna was an ancient city of Umbria that was controlled by Etruscans in the fourth century BCE.

209.name: Heba
209.description: A Roman colony that was established in the third or second century B.C., Heba lay near modern Magliano. Funerary evidence indicate previous Etruscan occupation at the site.

210.name: Cures
210.description: Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city in the Tiber River valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 B.C. under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.

211.name: Horta
211.description: The Etruscan settlement of *Hurta (the modern Orte) was close to the Vadimonis Lacus where the Romans fought, and won, two engagements against Etruscan armies.

212.name: Faesulae
212.description: Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul, Viśl, or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.

213.name: Firmum Picenum
213.description: Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 B.C. with 6,000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 B.C.

214.name: Piammiano
214.description: Site of an ancient settlement that flourished between the seventh century BCE and the early sixth century CE, located west across the Tiber from the modern village of Attigliano in Italy. Piammiano is probably to be identified with "Statonia", which is mentioned in ancient sources.

215.name: Sentinum
215.description: An ancient town in the region of Italy now known as Le Marche, Sentinum is perhaps best known for the pivotal Battle of Sentinum of the Third Samnite War that took place nearby in 295 BC.

216.name: Visentium
216.description: Visentium (Bisenzio) was an Etruscan settlement located on the shores of Lago di Bolsena. The site has yielded especially important evidence for Iron Age and Etruscan period burials.

217.name: Velzna/*Volsinii Veteres/Urbiventus
217.description: Volsinii Veteres was one of the most powerful and important cities of Etruria, as it was the location of the important federal sanctuary located at the Fanum Voltumnae.

218.name: Tarchna/Tarquinii
218.description: An ancient city of Etruria and the leading city of the doudecim populi Etruriae, Tarquinia (called Tarch(u)na or Tarchna in Etruscan) was a major urban center of ancient Italy.

219.name: Vulci
219.description: Vulci (originally Velch or Velx in Etruscan) was an Etruscan city 80 km northwest of Rome. Vulci was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae.

220.name: Teate
220.description: Originally named Teate Marrucinorum, Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.

221.name: Ocriculum
221.description: An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.

222.name: Plestia
222.description: Plestia was a municipium of the tribus Ufentina.

223.name: Nequinum/Narnia
223.description: Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.

224.name: Perusia
224.description: A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin, Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century B.C. during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late, in A.D. 251-3, under Trebonianus Gallus.

225.name: Lychnidos
225.description: Lychnidos (modern Ohrid, Macedonia) is an ancient city listed as UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979 and 1980 for both its cultural and natural heritage.

226.name: Dyrr(h)achium/Epidamnos
226.description: A city founded in 627 B.C. by colonists from Corinth and Kerkyra.

227.name: Herakleia
227.description: Herakleia or Herakleia Lynkestis was an ancient city of Macedonia founded by Philip II of Macedon in the middle of the fourth century B.C.

228.name: Apollonia
228.description: Ancient Greek trade colony which developed into an independent polis, and later a Roman city, in southern Illyria

229.name: Saepinum
229.description: An ancient town of Samnium captured by the Romans in 293 B.C., located on the road between Beneventum and Corfinium.

230.name: Pyrgi
230.description: Pyrgi is an ancient Etruscan port city on the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy. A Roman colony was established at the site by 191 B.C. In 1964 the bi-lingual 'Pyrgi Plaques' were discovered during the course of excavations.

231.name: Privernum
231.description: A Volscian center that Rome reportedly destroyed in the late fourth century B.C.

232.name: Teanum Sidicinum
232.description: Teanum Sidicinum (modern Teano) was the capital of the Oscan-speaking Sidicini tribe. The city likely submitted to Rome after 334 B.C.

233.name: Saticula
233.description: Saticula was a Samnite site in Campania that received a Latin colony in 313 B.C.

234.name: Suessula
234.description: Suessula was an important ancient city of Campania.

235.name: Suessa Aurunca
235.description: The ancient center of the Aurunci, Suessa Aurunca was abandoned in 337 B.C. for a more favorable site (modern Sessa) where a Latin colony was established in 313 B.C.

236.name: Nola
236.description: The city of Nola (Nuvlana) is considered one of the oldest in Campania. Under Augustus the settlement became a Roman colony; it was the spot where Augustus died in A.D. 14.

237.name: Dikaiarcheia/Puteoli
237.description: A maritime city of Campania situated on the Phlegrean Peninsula. The settlement started as a Greek colony and became a Roman colony under the name Puteoli in 194 B.C.

238.name: Cumae/Kyme (Campanian)
238.description: An ancient settlement of Campania, Cumae was the first Greek colony established on the Italian mainland in the eighth century BC.

239.name: Caudium
239.description: A city of Samnium located between Capua and Beneventum. In 321 B.C. the Samnites under C. Pontius encamped there before defeating the Romans at the battle of the Caudine Forks.

240.name: Cales (Campania)
240.description: Cales was an ancient city of Campania of Ausonian origins. The Romans captured the town in 335 B.C. and established a colony there.

241.name: Calatia
241.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Calatia

242.name: Carsioli
242.description: An ancient settlement along the Via Valeria, Carsioli was established as a Latin colony in the territory of the Aequi ca. 298 BC.

243.name: Capua
243.description: An important ancient city of Campania with Villanovan and Etruscan origins.

244.name: Canusium
244.description: A center of the ancient Daunians, Canusium became allied to Rome in 318 B.C. It received municipal status in 88 B.C.

245.name: Brundisium/Brentesion
245.description: A Greek and Roman port, terminus of the Via Appia.

246.name: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon)
246.description: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon) was originally a Daunian city. It was named as a Colonia Togata in 320 B.C. and came to play a significant role in the Second Punic War. Constans II sacked the town in A.D. 663.

247.name: Metapontum
247.description: An important city of Magna Graecia, Metapontum was located on the Gulf of Tarentum. The Achaeans were responsible for its foundation, perhaps as early as the eighth century B.C.

248.name: Grumentum
248.description: Grumentum was an ancient settlement of Lucania, likely inhabited since the sixth century B.C. The site played a role in the Second Punic War and later became a bishopric in the fourth century A.D.

249.name: Signia
249.description: A city of Latium Adjectum established as a Latin colony ca. 494 B.C.

250.name: Praeneste
250.description: An ancient city of central Italy, the eighth and seventh century B.C. origins of which demonstrate high-level trade contact with the Eastern Mediterranean world. The city withdrew from the Latin League (499 B.C.) and opposed Rome in the Latin war; Cincinnatus eventually subdued Praeneste. Sulla founded a new colony there in the first century B.C.

251.name: Velitrae
251.description: Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period, Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 B.C. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.

252.name: Tusculum
252.description: Tusculum was a Latin city of the Alban Hills in central Italy. After 381 B.C., Tusculum became the first "municipium cum suffragio".

253.name: Ostia
253.description: The port city of ancient Rome located at the mouth of the river Tiber.

254.name: Norba
254.description: Norba, located in the Monti Lepini, was a member of the Latin League (ca. 499 B.C.) and became a Latin colony ca. 492 B.C. The city was destroyed in the early first century B.C.

255.name: Lavinium
255.description: An ancient city of Latium on the Numicus River that was founded, according to Virgil, by Aeneas.

256.name: Caere
256.description: Caere (also known as Cisra or Cerveteri) was a major Etruscan polis located ca. 50 km north-northwest of Rome in southern Etruria.

257.name: Aricia
257.description: Aricia is an ancient Latin settlement and a member of the Latin League.

258.name: Alsium
258.description: Alsium served as a port for Caere, together with Fregenae.

259.name: Antium
259.description: Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for its number of coastal villas.

260.name: Ardea
260.description: Ardea was an ancient settlement of the Rutuli in Latium.

261.name: Nora
261.description: A pre-Roman and Roman site in southern Sardinia.

262.name: Alalie/Aleria
262.description: A city of Corsica with significant pre-historic, Greek, Etruscan, and Roman phases.

263.name: Tharros
263.description: An ancient Phoenician settlement located in western Sardinia on a promontory in the Gulf of Oristano, just south of modern San Giovanni di Sinis. While it originates as a Punic or Carthaginian settlement ca. 700 BCE, it continued as a major town in Roman times.

264.name: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana
264.description: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana (modern Cadiz, Spain) is an ancient city of Spain and one of the oldest continuously occupied cities of Europe. Its origins may be Phoenician (Gadir (Phoenician: גדר)).

265.name: Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium
265.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B2 Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium

266.name: Ilici/Helike
266.description: The site of Ilici began as a pre-Roman settlement that eventually developed into a Roman municipium. The site continued into the Visigothic and Byzantine periods as a minor urban settlement, controlling a vast territory which reached old Lucentum. The settlement was relocated to the modern site of Elche in the Islamic period.

267.name: Saguntum/Arse
267.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Saguntum/Arse

268.name: Icosium
268.description: Icosium (modern Algiers) was a Punic and, later, Roman settlement in coastal north Africa. Legend holds that 20 of Herakles' companions founded the original town.

269.name: Iol Caesarea
269.description: Iol Caesarea (modern Cherchell, Algeria) is a seaport with Punic and Roman phases.

270.name: Odessus
270.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E5 Odessus

271.name: Kabyle/Diospolis
271.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 D6 Kabyle/Diospolis

272.name: Histria
272.description: Histria was a Greek colony founded near the mouths of the Danube ca. 630 BC.

273.name: Mesembria
273.description: Originally a Thracian site known as Menebria, Mesembria was subsequently settled by Dorian Greeks in the early sixth century BC, eventually becoming an important trading colony on the Black Sea coast (modern Nesebar, Bulgaria). Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983.

274.name: Apollonia Pontica/Sozopolis
274.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E6 Apollonia Pontica/Sozopolis

275.name: Dionysopolis/Krounoi
275.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 F5 Dionysopolis/Krounoi

276.name: Tomis
276.description: Tomis was founded as a Greek colony on the Black Sea coast ca. 600 B.C.

277.name: Siga
277.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D1 Siga

278.name: Emporiae
278.description: A major economic center in the Iberian peninsula, Emporiae (modern Empúries) had indigenous origins but would be the site of a large Greek colonial city.

279.name: Col. Tarraco
279.description: An Iberian site in contact with Greek and Phoenician merchants that became a major Roman center from the third century BC onward.

280.name: Chersonesos
280.description: Chersonesos was an ancient Greek colony founded in the southwestern part of the Crimean Peninsula, ancient Taurica. Settlers from Heraclea Pontica established the site in the sixth century B.C.

281.name: Borysthenes/Olbia
281.description: Commonly referred to as "Olbia Pontica" to distinguish it from multiple other ancient sites with the same name, the remains of this multi-period settlement are located immediately south of the modern Ukrainian village of Parutyne on the west bank of the Dnieper–Bug Estuary.

282.name: Kalos Limen?
282.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 F3 Kalos Limen?

283.name: Tyras/Ophioussa
283.description: A Black Sea colony founded by Miletus.

284.name: Tingi
284.description: Tingi (modern Tangier) began as a Carthaginian colony of the early 5th century BC. A commercial center, Tingi came under the Roman sphere in the first century BC, initially as a free city but later as the site of a colony (Colonia Julia) under Claudius and the capital of Mauritania Tingitana.

285.name: Hermopolis Magna/Schmun
285.description: The capital city of the Hermopolite nome (the fifteenth Nome of Upper Egypt). The ancient Egyptians called the site Khmun after the group of eight divinities (Ogdoad) that represented the primordial world.

286.name: Lapethos/Lepethis Phoinikon
286.description: Located on the north coast of Cyprus 10 km west of Keryneia, Lapethos/Lepethis Phoinikon is known through archaeological remains for the most part. Archaeological evidence shows settlement already in the Late Bronze Age, continuing to the first millennium BCE and beyond. The tradition of Lapethos holds that the kingdom was founded by Praxandros from Lakonia in the Peloponnese.

287.name: Idalion
287.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Idalion

288.name: (Nea) Paphos
288.description: The legendary birthplace of the goddess Aphrodite, (Nea) Paphos has been a center of activity since the Final Bronze Age when Mycenaeans honored the goddess there. The site was listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1980.

289.name: Salamis/Konstantia
289.description: An ancient settlement on the east coast of Cyprus, located northwest of Ammokhostos.

290.name: Soloi/Aipeia?
290.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 B2 Soloi/Aipeia?

291.name: Amathous
291.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C3 Amathous

292.name: Premis
292.description: Qasr Ibrim is an archaeological site in Lower Nubia. The site has a long history of occupation stretching from the eighth century B.C. to 1813.

293.name: Venta
293.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F3 Venta

295.name: Paraetonium/Ammonia
295.description: The westernmost town of ancient Egypt.

296.name: Eileithyiaspolis
296.description: Eileithyiaspolis is a city of Upper Egypt on the eastern bank of the Nile river. The site was occupied from the Neolithic period onwards. Its ancient name was most likely Nekheb.

297.name: Syene
297.description: The ancient city of Swenett in Egypt, called Syene by the Greeks.

298.name: Krokodilopolis/Ptolemais Euergetis
298.description: An ancient city in the Heptanomis and the capital of Arsinoites nome. The ancient Egyptian name of the site was Shedyet and in Pharaonic times it was a major cult center for the god Sobek.

299.name: Memphis
299.description: A city and capital of Ancient Egypt that remained an important center for most of Egyptian history.

300.name: Oxyrhynchus/Pemje
300.description: A city of Upper Egypt, Oxyrhynchus/Pemje is particularly well known as an archaeological site that has produced important papyrus manuscripts of ancient texts.

301.name: Aelana/Aila
301.description: The city of Aqaba on the Red Sea.

302.name: Bouto
302.description: Modern Tell/Kawm el-Fara’in, located in Egypt's Nile delta. The site was a locus of human settlement and activity from the prehistoric period through the early Islamic period.

303.name: Canopus
303.description: An ancient Egyptian city of the Nile river delta. Canopus was located in the seventh nome (Menelaites) on the western bank at the mouth of the westernmost branch of the Nile.

304.name: Athribis (Lower Egypt)
304.description: An ancient city of Lower Egypt located at present-day Tell Atrib to the northeast of Benha on the hill of Kom Sidi Yusuf.

305.name: Pelusium
305.description: Pelusium was a fortified ancient city located at the mouth of the eastern-most branch of the Nile river. Its ruins, now land-locked and located approximately 30km southeast of Port Said, are known as Tell Farama.

306.name: Letopolis
306.description: Letopolis was an ancient Egyptian city. It served as the capital of the second nome of Lower Egypt.

307.name: Mendes
307.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F3 Mendes

308.name: Naucratis
308.description: Naucratis was a city of the Nile river delta, located on the Canopic branch. Capital of Ptolemaic Egypt, Naucratis was the site of permanent Greek habitation from the sixth century BC onward.

309.name: Heliopolis
309.description: Ancient Heliopolis was the capital of the 13th or Heliopolite Nome of Lower Egypt and served as a major religious center. The site is now located in Ayn Shams, a suburb of Cairo.

310.name: Sebennytos
310.description: Sebennytos was an ancient city of Lower Egypt located on the Sebennytic branch of the Nile river. It was the capital of Lower Egypt's twelfth nome (the Sebennyte nome).

311.name: Sais
311.description: Sais was an ancient Egyptian town located in the Western Nile Delta on the Canopic branch of the Nile river. It served as the provincial capital of Sap-Meh, the fifth nome of Lower Egypt, and became a capital during the Twenty-fourth Dynasty (ca. 732–720 BC) as well as during the Late Period. Herodotus claimed that Osiris was buried at Sais. Other Greek authors, including Plato, maintained a connection between Sais and the goddess Athena.

312.name: Thmouis
312.description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F3 Thmouis
